(8, '2024', 'College of Computing Studies', 'Fuentiblanca, Igyluis', '2025-11-11', '\"Title: DeepDetect: DeepFaked Media Detector\\n          Abstract: The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence has led to the creation of highly realistic synthetic media, commonly known as deepfakes. These manipulated videos, images, and audio clips pose serious threats to digital integrity, misinformation control, and public trust. DeepDetect is an AI-driven system designed to accurately identify and flag deepfaked media using advanced deep learning models such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and recurrent neural networks (RNNs). The system analyzes facial inconsistencies, pixel-level artifacts, and temporal irregularities to distinguish between genuine and altered content. Through extensive testing and dataset training, DeepDetect demonstrates high accuracy and reliability in detecting deepfakes, offering a scalable solution for media verification in journalism, social media platforms, and cybersecurity contexts.\\n          Conclusion: DeepDetect provides a critical defense mechanism against the growing challenge of deepfake technology. By leveraging deep learning and image analysis, the system enhances digital security and promotes authenticity in online media. Its application can help prevent the spread of misinformation, protect individuals from identity manipulation, and support ethical AI use across digital ecosystems. Future improvements may include integrating real-time detection capabilities and cross-platform compatibility to strengthen trust in digital communication. Ultimately, DeepDetect contributes to building a safer, more transparent information environment.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Assessing Emotional State in EARIST Students through Machine Learning Analysis of Vocal Tone During Pocket Book Reading \\n          Abstract: The emotional well-being of students plays a crucial role in their academic performance and overall mental health. This study, “Assessing Emotional State in EARIST Students through Machine Learning Analysis of Vocal Tone During Pocket Book Reading,” explores how voice-based emotion recognition can provide insights into students’ emotional states. Using machine learning models such as Support Vector Machines (SVM) and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN), the system analyzes vocal tone, pitch, frequency, and intensity during pocket book reading sessions. The goal is to detect emotional indicators such as happiness, sadness, stress, or calmness. Data were collected from recorded voice samples of EARIST students and processed through audio feature extraction techniques like MFCC (Mel Frequency Cepstral Coefficients). The results demonstrate that machine learning can effectively classify emotional states with promising accuracy, offering a new perspective on emotional assessment in educational settings.\\n          Conclusion: The findings of this study show that vocal tone analysis using machine learning can serve as a reliable and non-intrusive method for assessing students’ emotional well-being. By identifying emotional patterns through speech, educators and counselors can better understand students’ mental and emotional conditions, leading to improved support systems and learning environments. This approach not only enhances emotional awareness but also promotes mental health monitoring using innovative technology. Future studies may include real-time emotion tracking and multimodal data integration, such as facial expressions and physiological signals, to improve accuracy and applicability in educational psychology.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Detecting Malicious Advertisements Through Text and Image: A Fusion Approach Using Naïve Bayes and CNN Algorithms\\n          Abstract: The increasing prevalence of malicious online advertisements poses significant threats to user privacy, cybersecurity, and digital trust. This study, “Detecting Malicious Advertisements Through Text and Image: A Fusion Approach Using Naïve Bayes and CNN Algorithms,” proposes a hybrid detection system that integrates both textual and visual analysis for improved accuracy. The textual content of advertisements is processed and classified using the Naïve Bayes algorithm to identify suspicious keywords and linguistic patterns, while the image components are analyzed through a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to detect deceptive or inappropriate visual elements. By fusing the results of both models, the system achieves a higher precision rate in identifying malicious ads compared to single-modality methods. Experimental evaluations demonstrate that the fusion approach enhances detection reliability, helping users and organizations filter harmful online content effectively.\\n          Conclusion: The fusion of text-based and image-based analysis provides a robust solution for detecting malicious advertisements. By combining the strengths of Naïve Bayes in text classification and CNN in image recognition, the system successfully identifies potential threats that might bypass traditional detection methods. This research contributes to enhancing online safety, protecting users from phishing, scams, and malware embedded in digital advertisements. Future work may involve real-time ad monitoring, integration with web browsers, and expansion to multilingual datasets for broader applicability. Overall, this study underscores the importance of intelligent, AI-driven systems in promoting a safer digital ecosystem.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: QLBase: Decentralizable backend solution alternative to traditional noSQL and cloudbased services using ACID and LZW Algorithm\\n          Abstract: The growing reliance on centralized cloud-based and NoSQL databases raises concerns about data privacy, scalability, and system dependency on third-party providers. QLBase proposes a decentralizable backend solution designed to address these limitations by integrating ACID-compliant transaction management with LZW (Lempel–Ziv–Welch) compression for optimized data storage and transmission. The system enables distributed nodes to store and process data securely while maintaining consistency, reliability, and performance comparable to conventional centralized databases. By implementing a hybrid data structure and efficient compression scheme, QLBase minimizes latency and bandwidth usage, providing a lightweight yet robust backend alternative. Experimental evaluations demonstrate that QLBase offers improved fault tolerance, reduced operational cost, and enhanced control over data ownership—key factors for modern decentralized application (dApp) architectures.\\n          Conclusion: QLBase presents an innovative step toward decentralizing backend systems while maintaining the stability and reliability of traditional database models. Through the use of ACID principles, it ensures data integrity and transaction safety, while LZW compression enhances efficiency and resource utilization. The proposed system promotes user autonomy, resilience, and transparency in data management, addressing critical challenges in centralized infrastructures. Future work may explore blockchain integration, multi-node synchronization optimization, and cross-platform deployment to strengthen its applicability for large-scale decentralized ecosystems. Ultimately, QLBase contributes to advancing open, secure, and efficient digital infrastructure for next-generation applications.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: ResearchKoTo: A WebBased AI - Driven Contextual Analysis of Scientific Articles for Review of Related Studies\\n          Abstract: Conducting a Review of Related Studies (RRS) is a critical yet time-consuming step in academic research, often requiring extensive reading and analysis of numerous scientific articles. ResearchKoTo is a web-based, AI-driven system designed to streamline this process by automatically performing contextual analysis of research papers. Using Natural Language Processing (NLP) and machine learning algorithms, the system identifies key themes, summarizes related literature, and classifies studies based on research domains and methodologies. By processing abstracts and full-text content, ResearchKoTo helps users extract relevant information more efficiently, reducing manual workload and improving the accuracy of literature synthesis. The platform provides an intelligent, user-friendly interface accessible to students, educators, and researchers, supporting data-driven and well-informed academic writing.\\n          Conclusion: ResearchKoTo demonstrates the potential of artificial intelligence in transforming academic research workflows. By leveraging contextual analysis through NLP, the system enhances the process of reviewing related studies, making it faster, more consistent, and less prone to human error. This innovation not only improves research efficiency but also encourages academic integrity and accessibility to scientific knowledge. Future developments may include integrating citation analysis, semantic search, and multilingual support to further expand its usability. Ultimately, ResearchKoTo contributes to the modernization of research methodologies and the promotion of intelligent academic tools for the digital era.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: An Advanced Integrated IntranetBased Simulation System for the College of Hospitality and Tourism Management of EARIST Manila\\n          Abstract: The College of Hospitality and Tourism Management (CHTM) of EARIST Manila requires a modern and efficient system to enhance academic training and administrative operations. This study, “An Advanced Integrated Intranet-Based Simulation System,” aims to develop a comprehensive platform designed to simulate real-world hospitality and tourism management processes within a controlled digital environment. The system integrates modules for hotel and restaurant operations, reservation management, event planning, and performance assessment, all accessible through the institution’s intranet. By providing an interactive, hands-on learning experience, the platform bridges the gap between theoretical instruction and practical application. It also supports faculty in monitoring student activities and generating analytical reports for academic evaluation. The implementation of this intranet-based simulation system demonstrates the potential of technology-driven education in improving learning engagement, operational efficiency, and institutional innovation.\\n          Conclusion: The development of the Advanced Integrated Intranet-Based Simulation System significantly enhances the teaching and learning experience within the College of Hospitality and Tourism Management. By providing a centralized and interactive platform, the system allows students to gain practical experience in a simulated professional environment while enabling instructors to manage, assess, and guide learners more effectively. This innovation not only improves educational outcomes but also strengthens institutional efficiency and digital transformation within EARIST Manila. Future improvements may include expanding system functionality to cover industry partnerships, online certifications, and real-time analytics. Overall, the project contributes to advancing education and preparing students for real-world challenges in the hospitality and tourism sector.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Detection of Abnormal Heartbeat using Audio Spectrogram and Hybrid CNN-LSTM Model \\n          Abstract: Cardiovascular diseases remain one of the leading causes of mortality worldwide, making early and accurate detection of abnormal heartbeats crucial. This study, “Detection of Abnormal Heartbeat Using Audio Spectrogram and Hybrid CNN-LSTM Model,” proposes an AI-driven approach for classifying heart sound signals. Heartbeat audio recordings are converted into spectrograms, capturing both temporal and frequency information, which are then analyzed using a hybrid Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model. The CNN component extracts spatial features from the spectrograms, while the LSTM captures temporal dependencies in the heartbeat patterns. Experimental results demonstrate that the hybrid model achieves high accuracy in distinguishing between normal and abnormal heart sounds, providing a reliable, non-invasive diagnostic tool for cardiovascular health monitoring.\\n          Conclusion: The hybrid CNN-LSTM model effectively detects abnormal heartbeats from audio spectrograms, combining spatial and temporal feature extraction for enhanced classification performance. This approach provides a promising, non-invasive method for early cardiovascular risk assessment, supporting timely medical intervention and continuous patient monitoring. Future enhancements may include real-time detection, integration with wearable devices, and deployment in telemedicine platforms to broaden accessibility. Overall, this system contributes to improving healthcare outcomes and promoting proactive management of heart-related conditions.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Predictive Modelling for Effective Study Time and Distraction Identification using Machine Learning\\n          Abstract: Effective study habits are critical for academic success, yet students often struggle with time management and distractions. This study, “Predictive Modelling for Effective Study Time and Distraction Identification Using Machine Learning,” proposes a data-driven approach to monitor and optimize students’ study patterns. By collecting behavioral and environmental data, including study duration, device usage, and engagement metrics, the system employs machine learning algorithms such as Random Forests, Support Vector Machines (SVM), and Gradient Boosting to predict optimal study times and detect periods of distraction. The predictive model provides actionable insights and personalized recommendations to enhance focus, productivity, and learning efficiency. Experimental evaluations indicate that the system accurately identifies distractions and suggests strategies for effective study planning, empowering students to improve academic performance.\\n          Conclusion: The predictive modelling framework successfully identifies distractions and recommends effective study periods using machine learning techniques. By offering personalized insights into study behavior, the system helps students manage time efficiently, reduce distractions, and enhance overall learning outcomes. Future improvements could include real-time monitoring, integration with mobile and web applications, and adaptive feedback based on user progress. Overall, this approach demonstrates the potential of AI-driven tools to support academic success and foster better study habits among students.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Transforming Distance Learning: Developing a Virtual Reality Application for Remote Education\\n          Abstract: The shift to remote education has highlighted the limitations of traditional online learning platforms, particularly in engagement and interactivity. This study, “Transforming Distance Learning: Developing a Virtual Reality (VR) Application for Remote Education,” presents a VR-based learning environment designed to enhance student engagement, collaboration, and comprehension. The application creates immersive simulations of classrooms, laboratories, and interactive educational scenarios, allowing students to experience realistic learning experiences from remote locations. Key features include real-time interaction, 3D visualization of concepts, and gamified learning activities. Initial user testing demonstrates increased engagement, improved understanding of complex topics, and higher motivation among students compared to conventional online learning methods.\\n          Conclusion: The development of a Virtual Reality application for remote education offers a transformative approach to distance learning by providing immersive, interactive, and engaging educational experiences. By bridging the gap between physical and virtual classrooms, the system enhances comprehension, retention, and collaboration among learners. Future developments may include integration with learning management systems, adaptive learning paths, and multi-user collaborative environments. Overall, this VR application contributes to improving access to quality education and fostering innovative teaching and learning methodologies.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: DentalSuite: Dynamic Solution for Dental Clinic Management System with\\n          Abstract: Efficient management of dental clinics is essential for improving patient care, optimizing operations, and ensuring accurate record-keeping. DentalSuite is a dynamic dental clinic management system designed to streamline administrative and clinical tasks through an integrated digital platform. The system provides modules for patient registration, appointment scheduling, treatment tracking, billing, inventory management, and reporting, all accessible via a user-friendly interface. By automating routine processes and centralizing patient information, DentalSuite reduces administrative errors, improves service efficiency, and enhances patient satisfaction. The system is designed to be scalable, adaptable, and secure, supporting clinics in delivering high-quality dental care.\\n          Conclusion: DentalSuite demonstrates a comprehensive solution for modern dental clinic management by integrating administrative, clinical, and financial functions into a single platform. The system improves workflow efficiency, enhances patient record management, and supports informed decision-making for dental practitioners. Future enhancements may include mobile accessibility, tele-dentistry integration, and AI-assisted diagnostic tools to further advance patient care. Overall, DentalSuite contributes to the modernization of dental services, promoting efficiency, accuracy, and quality in healthcare management.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Web-Based Tracking Employability of Alumni with Data Analytics for EARIST-Manila\\n          Abstract: Monitoring the employability of graduates is vital for assessing the effectiveness of academic programs and improving career support services. This study, “Web-Based Tracking Employability of Alumni with Data Analytics for EARIST-Manila,” proposes an integrated platform that collects, analyzes, and visualizes employment data of alumni. The system enables graduates to update their professional profiles while allowing administrators to track employment trends, job placements, and career progression. By leveraging data analytics, the platform provides insights into program effectiveness, skill gaps, and industry alignment. Initial testing demonstrates the system’s ability to generate actionable reports, support decision-making, and enhance alumni engagement.\\n          Conclusion: The web-based tracking system provides EARIST-Manila with a robust tool for monitoring alumni employability and improving academic program evaluation. By centralizing alumni data and applying analytics, the platform offers insights into career trends, helps identify skill gaps, and informs curriculum adjustments to better prepare students for the workforce. Future enhancements may include real-time reporting, integration with social and professional networks, and predictive analytics for career outcomes. Overall, this project contributes to strengthening the connection between education and employability, supporting informed decision-making and continuous program improvement.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: SafelyEqualizeIT: Facilitating Safe Transitioning for LGBTQIA+ Individuals through Web-based Consultation System for TransHealth PH\\n          Abstract: LGBTQIA+ individuals seeking gender-affirming healthcare often face barriers such as limited access to professional guidance, social stigma, and fragmented medical information. SafelyEqualizeIT addresses these challenges by providing a web-based consultation system designed to facilitate safe and informed transitioning for transgender individuals in the Philippines. The platform enables users to connect with certified healthcare providers, access educational resources, and receive personalized guidance on medical, psychological, and legal aspects of gender transition. Through secure communication channels and an intuitive interface, the system ensures confidentiality and accessibility. Preliminary user testing indicates improved knowledge, confidence, and access to professional support among the target community.\\n          Conclusion: SafelyEqualizeIT demonstrates a practical solution for supporting transgender individuals in navigating the complex process of gender transitioning safely and responsibly. By integrating web-based consultations with educational resources and professional guidance, the platform enhances accessibility, reduces risks associated with uninformed decisions, and promotes overall well-being. Future enhancements may include multilingual support, mobile application integration, and AI-driven resource recommendations. Overall, this project contributes to health equity, social inclusion, and empowerment of LGBTQIA+ individuals seeking gender-affirming care.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: EARIST SmartHandbook: An Android Student Handbook Application with Query bot for Student Assistance\\n          Abstract: Navigating academic life can be challenging for students without easy access to essential information and assistance. EARIST SmartHandbook is an Android-based student handbook application designed to centralize important institutional information and provide instant support through a query bot. The application allows students to access schedules, announcements, policies, campus facilities, and other academic resources conveniently on their mobile devices. The integrated query bot utilizes AI to answer student inquiries in real-time, reducing delays in obtaining information and enhancing overall campus engagement. User testing indicates increased accessibility, improved response efficiency, and greater student satisfaction.\\n          Conclusion: EARIST SmartHandbook provides a comprehensive solution to streamline student access to institutional information and assistance. By combining an intuitive Android interface with an AI-powered query bot, the application improves efficiency, supports academic planning, and enhances the overall student experience. Future developments may include personalized notifications, integration with learning management systems, and multilingual support to broaden accessibility. Overall, the project demonstrates the potential of mobile applications in improving student services, engagement, and academic success.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: SnapShop: A WebBased IGP Shop for EARIST Merchandise, Books, and Uniforms\\n          Abstract: Accessing official merchandise, books, and uniforms can be challenging for students and faculty, often requiring physical visits to campus stores. SnapShop is a web-based IGP shop designed to streamline the purchase of EARIST merchandise, academic books, and uniforms through an online platform. The system features an intuitive interface for browsing, selecting, and securely purchasing items, with options for payment and delivery tracking. By digitizing the campus retail experience, SnapShop improves accessibility, reduces queue times, and ensures convenience for the university community. Initial testing demonstrates high usability, faster transaction processing, and increased satisfaction among users.\\n          Conclusion: SnapShop provides a practical solution for modernizing campus retail operations, offering students and staff an efficient, accessible, and secure way to purchase merchandise, books, and uniforms. The platform enhances user experience, streamlines administrative processes, and supports campus operations by reducing in-person workload. Future improvements may include mobile app integration, inventory management optimization, and personalized recommendations for users. Overall, SnapShop contributes to the digital transformation of campus services, promoting convenience, efficiency, and user satisfaction.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Optimizing Library Usage Tracking at EARIST with Near Field Communication: Assessing Efficiency in Time Tracking and Record Accessibility\\n          Abstract: Efficient tracking of library usage is essential for managing resources, understanding student behavior, and improving service delivery. This study, “Optimizing Library Usage Tracking at EARIST with Near Field Communication (NFC),” introduces an NFC-based system to automate library check-ins, check-outs, and usage monitoring. By integrating NFC technology with a digital database, the system enables real-time recording of student activity, reduces manual errors, and ensures faster access to records. Experimental evaluation indicates enhanced accuracy, reduced processing time, and improved accessibility of usage data for both library staff and students, supporting more informed decision-making and resource management.\\n          Conclusion: The NFC-based library tracking system demonstrates a significant improvement in the efficiency and accuracy of monitoring library usage at EARIST. By automating time tracking and record management, the system minimizes manual errors, reduces administrative workload, and provides instant access to usage data. Future enhancements may include mobile app integration, advanced analytics for usage trends, and personalized recommendations for students based on reading habits. Overall, this project contributes to smarter library management, better resource allocation, and enhanced student experience.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Tarsie: Interactive Tagalog Animated E-Learning App for Pre-School Students\\n          Abstract: Early childhood education benefits greatly from engaging and interactive learning tools that foster language and cognitive development. Tarsie is an interactive Tagalog animated e-learning application designed for pre-school students to enhance language skills, literacy, and foundational knowledge through gamified lessons and storytelling. The app features animated characters, quizzes, and interactive exercises that encourage active participation while teaching basic vocabulary, numbers, and social concepts. Initial testing with young learners indicates improved engagement, better retention of lessons, and positive feedback from both students and educators.\\n          Conclusion: Tarsie provides an innovative approach to early childhood education by combining animation, interactivity, and culturally relevant content in Tagalog. The application enhances learning engagement, supports language development, and prepares students for foundational academic skills in a fun and accessible way. Future improvements may include expanding content, integrating adaptive learning paths, and providing parental or teacher dashboards to track progress. Overall, Tarsie contributes to quality early education, promoting cognitive development and fostering a love for learning among young learners.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Online Academic Performance Monitoring System for Eulogio Rodriguez Vocational High Schoo\\n          Abstract: Monitoring student academic performance is essential for identifying learning gaps, improving teaching strategies, and supporting student success. This study, “Online Academic Performance Monitoring System for Eulogio Rodriguez Vocational High School,” presents a web-based platform designed to track, manage, and analyze student performance in real-time. The system allows teachers to input grades, generate performance reports, and monitor progress, while students and parents can access dashboards to review academic standing and attendance. Initial testing shows that the platform reduces manual record-keeping, provides timely performance insights, and enhances communication among teachers, students, and parents.\\n          Conclusion: The online academic performance monitoring system improves the efficiency and accuracy of tracking student performance at Eulogio Rodriguez Vocational High School. By providing real-time access to grades, attendance, and progress reports, the platform supports informed decision-making for teachers, empowers students to take responsibility for their learning, and enhances parental engagement. Future developments may include predictive analytics for academic performance, mobile app integration, and personalized learning recommendations. Overall, this system contributes to better educational outcomes and a more effective, transparent academic management process.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Integration of Diagnostic and Prescriptive Analysis on a WebBased Agricultural E-commerce\\n          Abstract: Agricultural e-commerce platforms can benefit from data-driven insights to improve decision-making for both farmers and buyers. This study, “Integration of Diagnostic and Prescriptive Analysis on a Web-Based Agricultural E-Commerce,” presents a system that combines diagnostic analytics to understand past sales and crop trends with prescriptive analytics to recommend optimal actions for future production, pricing, and distribution. The web-based platform allows users to track market trends, analyze performance metrics, and receive actionable recommendations to maximize yield and profit. Initial testing demonstrates that integrating diagnostic and prescriptive analytics improves decision-making efficiency, enhances user engagement, and supports sustainable agricultural practices.\\n          Conclusion: The integration of diagnostic and prescriptive analytics within the web-based agricultural e-commerce platform empowers users to make informed decisions based on historical trends and actionable recommendations. By offering insights into market behavior, crop performance, and pricing strategies, the system supports farmers, buyers, and sellers in optimizing operations and improving profitability. Future enhancements may include real-time data integration, AI-driven predictive modeling, and mobile accessibility. Overall, this project contributes to more efficient, sustainable, and technology-driven agricultural commerce.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: EARISTour: A Webbased Panoramic Image to 360 Virtual Tour of Eulogio \\\"Amang\\\" Rodriguez Institute of Science and Technology Manila Campus\\n          Abstract: Campus tours are essential for prospective students, visitors, and stakeholders, but physical visits can be time-consuming or limited by accessibility. EARISTour is a web-based 360° virtual tour platform that converts panoramic images into immersive virtual experiences of the EARIST Manila campus. Users can navigate campus facilities, classrooms, and landmarks interactively from any device with an internet connection. The system enhances accessibility, provides an engaging way to explore campus resources, and serves as a tool for promotion and orientation. Initial testing shows improved user engagement, ease of navigation, and positive feedback from prospective students and visitors.\\n          Conclusion: EARISTour offers an innovative solution to campus exploration by providing a fully interactive, web-based 360° virtual tour. The platform enhances accessibility for users unable to visit the campus physically, promotes institutional visibility, and serves as a modern tool for orientation and engagement. Future enhancements may include integrating multimedia content, guided tours, and mobile application support. Overall, EARISTour contributes to digital campus experiences, improving accessibility, engagement, and institutional promotion.\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: E-Padyak Mobile Apps: A Key Factor for Sustainable Transportation Adoption in Pureza\\n          Abstract: Sustainable transportation solutions are critical for reducing urban congestion, lowering emissions, and promoting environmentally friendly commuting. E-Padyak Mobile Apps is a mobile application designed to facilitate the adoption of bike-sharing and sustainable transportation in the Pureza area. The app allows users to locate available bicycles, track rides, and manage payments while promoting eco-friendly commuting habits. By integrating real-time tracking, route suggestions, and usage analytics, the system encourages more residents to adopt cycling as a reliable transportation option. Initial testing shows increased user engagement, higher frequency of bicycle use, and a positive attitude toward sustainable commuting.\\n          Conclusion: E-Padyak Mobile Apps demonstrates the potential of mobile technology to promote sustainable transportation by providing convenience, accessibility, and real-time information for users. By encouraging the use of bicycles and other eco-friendly commuting options, the app contributes to reducing traffic congestion and environmental impact. Future developments may include integration with public transport, gamified incentives for regular users, and community-driven route optimization. Overall, this project supports sustainable urban mobility and fosters environmentally conscious commuting behaviors.\\n          Semester: 1st\"', '\"Title: Classification of Skin Allergies Using Convolutional Neural Network and Support Vector Machine\\n          Abstract: Skin allergies affect millions of individuals worldwide, and early detection is essential for effective treatment. This study presents a hybrid approach combining Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) and Support Vector Machines (SVM) for the classification of skin allergies based on image data. The CNN is used to extract relevant features from skin lesion images, which are then classified using SVM to improve accuracy and robustness. Experimental results demonstrate that this hybrid model achieves higher classification accuracy compared to traditional methods, enabling faster and more reliable diagnosis.\\n          Conclusion: The integration of CNN and SVM provides an effective solution for accurately classifying skin allergies, improving diagnostic reliability and speed. By leveraging deep feature extraction with robust classification, the system can assist medical professionals in early detection and treatment planning. Future enhancements may include expanding the dataset for rare allergy types, implementing mobile-based diagnostic applications, and incorporating explainable AI for better interpretability. Overall, this project contributes to improved healthcare delivery and early disease management.\\n          Funding Source: earist\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Decryption of Attendance , Monitoring of Senior High School Students , at ACTEC Using Zebra Crossing Algorithm\\n          Abstract: Accurate monitoring of student attendance is crucial for ensuring academic accountability and engagement. This study presents a system for attendance decryption and monitoring of Senior High School students at ACTEC using the Zebra Crossing Algorithm. The system captures student data through secure digital records, processes it using the algorithm to verify attendance, and generates automated reports for teachers and administrators. Preliminary results indicate improved efficiency in attendance tracking, reduced errors in record keeping, and enhanced monitoring of student participation.\\n          Conclusion: The implementation of the Zebra Crossing Algorithm in attendance monitoring provides a reliable, automated method for tracking Senior High School student presence. By ensuring accurate record-keeping and easy report generation, the system supports administrative efficiency and student accountability. Future improvements may include integration with mobile applications, real-time notifications, and data analytics for monitoring attendance trends. Overall, this project contributes to efficient school management and the promotion of responsible student engagement.\\n          Funding Source: self-funded\\n          Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: DIAFOODS: A Content Based Food Recommendation System for Diabetic Patients\\n          Abstract: Managing diet is critical for diabetic patients to maintain healthy blood sugar levels and overall well-being. DIAFOODS is a content-based food recommendation system designed to suggest meals tailored to the nutritional needs of diabetic individuals. The system analyzes food items based on their nutritional content, glycemic index, and dietary restrictions, providing personalized recommendations to users. Initial testing demonstrates that DIAFOODS can assist patients in making informed dietary choices, promote healthy eating habits, and reduce the risk of diabetes-related complications.\\n          Conclusion: DIAFOODS offers an effective solution for supporting diabetic patients in managing their diet through personalized food recommendations. By leveraging nutritional analysis and content-based filtering, the system helps users maintain balanced diets and make healthier meal choices. Future enhancements may include integration with mobile applications, real-time meal tracking, and machine learning models to improve recommendation accuracy. Overall, this project contributes to better health management, patient empowerment, and the prevention of diet-related complications.\\n          Funding Source: earist\\n          Semester: 2nd\"', '[{\"sdg\":9,\"total\":10},{\"sdg\":4,\"total\":9},{\"sdg\":3,\"total\":4}]', '**1. Diversify and Broaden SDG Research Topics**\n- Actively encourage student projects to address underrepresented SDGs through revised project guidelines and thematic calls.\n- Introduce new focus areas for student research, such as:\n  - SDG 13 (Climate Action) – Develop environmental monitoring applications.\n  - SDG 2 (Zero Hunger) – Create technology solutions for sustainable agriculture.\n  - SDG 6 (Clean Water and Sanitation) – Design systems for water quality management.\n\n**2. Foster Interdisciplinary Collaboration**\n- Establish partnerships between the CCS department and other academic units, such as Environmental Science and Social Sciences.\n- Organize joint seminars and workshops to expose IT students to challenges and perspectives related to a wider array of SDGs.\n- Create interdisciplinary project teams to develop more holistic and impactful solutions.\n\n**3. Enhance Curriculum Integration of SDGs**\n- Embed discussions and case studies of diverse SDGs throughout the Information Technology curriculum, beyond final year projects.\n- Introduce specialized elective courses focused on \"Technology for Sustainable Development\" to build student capacity.\n- Invite guest lecturers from non-governmental organizations and public sector agencies to present real-world problems related to various SDGs.\n\n**4. Incentivize and Track a Wider Range of Research**\n- Develop a system to track and report on faculty-led SDG research to provide a more comprehensive institutional overview.\n- Create departmental awards or recognitions for student and faculty research that addresses critical, underrepresented SDGs.\n- Pursue funding opportunities that specifically support research in areas like digital health, climate technology, and social equity.', '1. Concentrated Research Focus on Specific SDGs\n   • A significant majority of student research papers, totaling 75%, are concentrated on two Sustainable Development Goals.\n   • The most frequently addressed goals are SDG 4 (Quality Education) with 8 papers and SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure) with 7 papers.\n   • This focus aligns with the core curriculum of the Bachelor of Science in Information Technology program.\n\n2. Limited Scope of SDG Engagement\n   • The analysis indicates a narrow thematic range, with a large number of SDGs receiving no attention.\n   • Key environmental and social goals such as SDG 13 (Climate Action), SDG 14 (Life Below Water), and SDG 1 (No Poverty) are entirely absent from the student research output.\n   • Goals like SDG 5 (Gender Equality), SDG 8 (Decent Work and Economic Growth), and SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) are minimally represented with only one paper each.\n\n3. Exclusive Reliance on Undergraduate Data\n   • The current dataset is composed entirely of undergraduate student papers from a single academic program within the CCS department.\n   • There is a complete absence of data regarding faculty-led research or projects supported by external funding.\n   • This limitation means the report does not reflect the full spectrum of the department\'s research contributions to the SDGs.\n\n4. Underrepresentation of Health and Well-being Research\n   • Despite its relevance to technology, SDG 3 (Good Health and Well-being) is addressed in only 10% of the reviewed papers.\n   • This represents a potential area for growth, as information technology offers numerous solutions for healthcare challenges.\n   • The current output does not fully leverage the potential for IT students to contribute to digital health innovation.\n\n===SPLIT===\n\n1. Diversify and Broaden SDG Research Topics\n   • Actively encourage student projects to address underrepresented SDGs through revised project guidelines and thematic calls.\n   • Introduce new focus areas for student research, such as:\n     ▪ SDG 13 (Climate Action) – Develop environmental monitoring applications.\n     ▪ SDG 2 (Zero Hunger) – Create technology solutions for sustainable agriculture.\n     ▪ SDG 6 (Clean Water and Sanitation) – Design systems for water quality management.\n\n2. Foster Interdisciplinary Collaboration\n   • Establish partnerships between the CCS department and other academic units, such as Environmental Science and Social Sciences.\n   • Organize joint seminars and workshops to expose IT students to challenges and perspectives related to a wider array of SDGs.\n   • Create interdisciplinary project teams to develop more holistic and impactful solutions.\n\n3. Enhance Curriculum Integration of SDGs\n   • Embed discussions and case studies of diverse SDGs throughout the Information Technology curriculum, beyond final year projects.\n   • Introduce specialized elective courses focused on \"Technology for Sustainable Development\" to build student capacity.\n   • Invite guest lecturers from non-governmental organizations and public sector agencies to present real-world problems related to various SDGs.\n\n4. Incentivize and Track a Wider Range of Research\n   • Develop a system to track and report on faculty-led SDG research to provide a more comprehensive institutional overview.\n   • Create departmental awards or recognitions for student and faculty research that addresses critical, underrepresented SDGs.\n   • Pursue funding opportunities that specifically support research in areas like digital health, climate technology, and social equity.', 'models/gemini-2.5-pro', 5);
