(11, '2025', 'College of Computing Studies', 'Baris, Jomarie', '2025-11-14', '\"Title: qweqweqweqweqwe\\n            Abstract: N/A\\n            Conclusion: N/A\\n            Semester: 1st\"', '\"Title: Empowering Barangay Residents with Mobile Apps for Fire Response\\n            Abstract: Rapid response during fire emergencies is critical to minimizing damage and saving lives. This study presents a mobile application designed to empower barangay residents by providing real-time fire alerts, safety instructions, and emergency reporting tools. The app integrates location tracking, direct communication with fire response units, and educational resources to enhance preparedness and community engagement. Initial testing shows that residents are better informed, response times improve, and community coordination during fire incidents is strengthened.\\n            Conclusion: The mobile application effectively empowers barangay residents to respond promptly and safely during fire emergencies. By providing real-time alerts, educational resources, and direct communication with authorities, the system enhances community preparedness and reduces potential losses. Future improvements may include AI-based risk assessment, integration with municipal emergency systems, and multilingual support for broader accessibility. Overall, this project contributes to community resilience, public safety, and disaster preparedness at the local level.\\n            Funding Source: earist\\n            Semester: 1st\\n\\nTitle: Optimizing Export - Import Strategies for Economic Growth in the Philippines\\n            Abstract: Trade plays a pivotal role in driving economic growth, and optimizing export-import strategies is essential for national development. This study examines current trade practices in the Philippines and identifies key strategies to enhance export performance while efficiently managing imports. Using data analysis, policy evaluation, and forecasting models, the research provides insights into trade balance optimization, sector prioritization, and supply chain improvements. Findings highlight the potential for increased revenue, competitive advantage, and sustainable economic growth through strategic trade management.\\n            Conclusion: Optimizing export-import strategies can significantly contribute to the Philippines’ economic growth by improving trade efficiency, increasing competitiveness, and maximizing revenue from key sectors. Strategic recommendations include diversification of export products, strengthening trade partnerships, and implementing data-driven policy decisions to manage imports effectively. Future research may focus on integrating technological innovations, trade automation, and global market trend analysis to further enhance trade outcomes. Overall, this study supports sustainable economic development and improved global trade positioning for the Philippines.\\n            Funding Source: earist\\n            Semester: 1st\"', '[{\"sdg\":11,\"total\":2},{\"sdg\":8,\"total\":1},{\"sdg\":12,\"total\":1}]', '**1. Diversify and Broaden SDG Research Themes**\n- Encourage new research initiatives that address underrepresented SDGs to create a more balanced institutional portfolio.\n- Promote studies focusing on critical areas such as:\n  - SDG 4 (Quality Education) – Developing innovative educational technologies.\n  - SDG 13 (Climate Action) – Creating systems for environmental monitoring.\n- Offer incentives or grants for projects targeting less-addressed global goals.\n\n**2. Enhance Student Engagement in SDG Research**\n- Develop programs to increase student participation in SDG-focused research projects.\n- Integrate SDG-related capstone or thesis topics into the curriculum for both Computer Science and Information Technology programs.\n- Establish a mentorship program connecting students with faculty engaged in SDG research.\n\n**3. Foster Inter-Programmatic Collaboration**\n- Facilitate joint research projects between the Computer Science and Information Technology programs.\n- These collaborations can leverage the unique strengths of each discipline to address complex SDG challenges more effectively.\n- Host departmental workshops and seminars to showcase opportunities for cross-disciplinary SDG research.\n\n**4. Strengthen and Formalize SDG Tracking**\n- Implement a more granular system for classifying research contributions against specific SDG targets and indicators, not just the overarching goals.\n- Regularly review and report on the department\'s collective progress toward addressing the SDGs.\n- Utilize this data to strategically guide future research directions and resource allocation.', '1. Key SDG Focus Areas in Research Output\n   • The department\'s research primarily aligns with a select group of Sustainable Development Goals.\n   • SDG 11 (Sustainable Cities and Communities) is the most frequently addressed goal across both faculty and student papers.\n   • Other prominent goals include SDG 8 (Decent Work and Economic Growth), SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure), and SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production).\n\n2. Analysis of Research Contribution by Source\n   • Faculty research constitutes the majority of the SDG-related output, contributing two distinct papers.\n   • Student research is represented by a single paper, indicating a potential area for growth.\n   • Faculty papers demonstrate a broader scope, each addressing two distinct SDGs, whereas the student paper focuses on a single goal.\n\n3. Departmental and Programmatic Scope\n   • All documented SDG-aligned research originates from the CCS department, indicating a concentrated effort within this academic unit.\n   • The research is linked to specific degree programs, namely the Bachelor of Science in Computer Science and the Bachelor of Science in Information Technology.\n   • There is a clear division, with student research linked to Computer Science and faculty research to Information Technology in this dataset.\n\n4. Gaps in SDG Coverage\n   • A significant number of the 17 SDGs are not represented in the current research portfolio.\n   • Goals pertaining to environmental sustainability (e.g., Climate Action, Life Below Water) and social equity (e.g., No Poverty, Zero Hunger) are absent.\n   • The existing research focuses heavily on infrastructure, economic, and urban development themes.\n\n===SPLIT===\n\n1. Diversify and Broaden SDG Research Themes\n   • Encourage new research initiatives that address underrepresented SDGs to create a more balanced institutional portfolio.\n   • Promote studies focusing on critical areas such as:\n     ▪ SDG 4 (Quality Education) – Developing innovative educational technologies.\n     ▪ SDG 13 (Climate Action) – Creating systems for environmental monitoring.\n   • Offer incentives or grants for projects targeting less-addressed global goals.\n\n2. Enhance Student Engagement in SDG Research\n   • Develop programs to increase student participation in SDG-focused research projects.\n   • Integrate SDG-related capstone or thesis topics into the curriculum for both Computer Science and Information Technology programs.\n   • Establish a mentorship program connecting students with faculty engaged in SDG research.\n\n3. Foster Inter-Programmatic Collaboration\n   • Facilitate joint research projects between the Computer Science and Information Technology programs.\n   • These collaborations can leverage the unique strengths of each discipline to address complex SDG challenges more effectively.\n   • Host departmental workshops and seminars to showcase opportunities for cross-disciplinary SDG research.\n\n4. Strengthen and Formalize SDG Tracking\n   • Implement a more granular system for classifying research contributions against specific SDG targets and indicators, not just the overarching goals.\n   • Regularly review and report on the department\'s collective progress toward addressing the SDGs.\n   • Utilize this data to strategically guide future research directions and resource allocation.', 'models/gemini-2.5-pro', 4);

